{"title_page": "Ben Johnson (actor)", "text_new": "{{other people||Ben Johnson (disambiguation){{!}}Ben Johnson}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ben Johnson\n| image = Ben Johnson The Wild Bunch publicity photo.JPG\n| caption = Johnson in 1969\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1918|6|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Foraker, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1996|4|8|1918|6|13}}\n| death_place = [[Mesa, Arizona]], U.S.\n| nationality  = American\n| spouse = Carol Elaine Jones (1941&ndash;1994; her death)\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1939\u20131996\n}}\n\n'''Ben''' \"'''Son'''\" '''Johnson Jr.''' (June 13, 1918 \u2013 April 8, 1996) was an American [[stunt performer|stuntman]], world champion [[rodeo]] [[cowboy]], and [[Academy Award]]-winning actor. The son of a rancher, Johnson arrived in Hollywood to deliver a consignment of horses for a film. He did stunt-double work for several years before breaking into acting with the help of [[John Ford]]. Tall and laconic, Johnson brought authenticity to many roles in [[Western (genre)|Westerns]] with his expert horsemanship. An [[elegiac]] portrayal of a former cowboy theater owner in the 1950s coming-of-age drama, ''[[The Last Picture Show]]'', won Johnson the 1971 [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. He operated a horse-breeding ranch throughout his career. Although he said he had succeeded by sticking to what he knew, shrewd real estate investments made Johnson worth an estimated $100 million by his latter years.<ref name=Jensen>{{cite book|title=The Nicest Fella - the Life of Ben Johnson: The World Champion Rodeo Cowboy who Became an Oscar-winning Movie Star|first=Richard D.|last=Jensen|publisher=iUniverse|year=2010|isbn=9781440196782}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson was born in [[Foraker, Oklahoma]], on the [[Osage Nation|Osage Indian Reservation]], of [[Irish American|Irish]] and [[Cherokee]] ancestry,<ref name=ThurmanT-TCotR>{{cite web|last1=Thurman|first1=Tom|title=Ben Johnson: Third Cowboy on the Right|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0115653|accessdate=April 30, 2018|date=September 1, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"EricksonH-AM\">{{cite web|last1=Erickson|first1=Hal|title=Ben Johnson profile|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/ben-johnson-p35776|website=AllMovie|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref> the son of Ollie Susan Johnson (n\u00e9e Workmon; 1899-2000) and Ben Johnson, Sr. (1896-1952).<ref>[http://ftp.rootsweb.com/pub/usgenweb/ok/osage/obits/lssnwrdr.txt Ollie Susan Workmon Rider obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218075855/http://ftp.rootsweb.com/pub/usgenweb/ok/osage/obits/lssnwrdr.txt |date=2008-02-18 }}, Osage County, Oklahoma USGenWeb Project,  Rootsweb.com; accessed June 24, 2015.</ref> His father was a rancher and rodeo champion in [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage County]]. Johnson was drawn to the rodeos and horse breeding of his early years. In 1953, he took a break from well-paid film work to compete in the [[Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association]] (PRCA) becoming Team Roping World Champion, although he only broke even financially that year. Johnson was inducted into the [[ProRodeo Hall of Fame]] in 1973.<ref name=\"prorodeo\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.prorodeohalloffame.com/inductees/by-category/team-roping/ben-johnson/|title=Ben Johnson - Pro Rodeo Hall of Fame|work=Pro Rodeo Hall of Fame|access-date=April 12, 2017}}</ref> According to his ProRodeo Hall of Fame entry, he said, \"I've won a rodeo world championship, and I'm prouder of that than anything else I've ever done.\"<ref name=\"prorodeo\" /> In 2003, he was inducted into the [[Texas Trail of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Johnson|url=http://texastrailoffame.org/inductees/ben-johnson/|website=Western Heritage from the [[Texas Trail of Fame]]|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> Johnson's mother Ollie died a few years after her son, on October 16, 2000, aged 101.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080620142857/http://www.prorodeo.com/champions.aspx?xu=50 Profile], prorodeo.com; accessed June 24, 2015.</ref>\n\nJohnson's 1941 marriage to Carol Elaine Jones lasted until her death on March 27, 1994. They had no children. She was the daughter of noted Hollywood horse wrangler Clarence \"Fat\" Jones.<ref name=\"Jensen\"/>\n\n==Career==\nJohnson's film career began with the [[Howard Hughes]] film ''[[The Outlaw]]''. Before filming began, Hughes bought some horses at the Oklahoma ranch that Johnson's father managed, and hired Johnson to get the horses to northern Arizona (for ''The Outlaw'''s location shooting), and then to take them on to Hollywood.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\nJohnson liked to say later that he got to Hollywood in a carload of horses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jwayne.com/1996/05/01/a-tribute-to-ben-johnson/|title=Ben Johnson|publisher=JWayne.com|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> With his experience wrangling for Hughes during ''The Outlaw'''s location shooting, once in Hollywood, he did stunt work for the 1939 movie [[The Fighting Gringo (1939 film)|''The Fighting Gringo'']], and throughout the 1940s, he found work [[Wrangler (profession)|wrangling horses]] and doing stunt work involving horses.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\nHis work as a stuntman caught the eye of [[film director|director]] [[John Ford]]. Ford hired Johnson for stunt work in the 1948 film [[Fort Apache (film)|''Fort Apache'']], and as the riding double for [[Henry Fonda]].<ref name=EricksonH-AM/> During shooting, the horses pulling a wagon with three men in it stampeded. Johnson, who \"happened to be settin' on a horse\", stopped the runaway wagon and saved the men. When Ford promised that he would be rewarded, Johnson hoped it would be with another doubling job, or maybe a small speaking role.<ref name=BrownDG-AC-1995>{{cite journal|author=Brown, David G.|date=September\u2013October 1995|title=Last of a Breed|journal=American Cowboy|publisher=Active Interest Media|page=43|volume= 2|issue=3|issn=1079-3690}}</ref> Instead he received a seven-year acting contract from Ford.<ref>{{cite book|author=McBride, Joseph|year=2003|title=Searching for John Ford: A Life|publisher=Macmillan|page=496|isbn=978-0-312-31011-0}}</ref> Ford called Johnson into his office, handed him an envelope with a contract in it. Johnson started reading it and when he got to the fifth line and it said \"$5,000 a week,\" he stopped reading, grabbed a pen, and signed it, and gave it back to Ford.<ref name=BrownDG-AC-1995/>\n\n[[File:WagonMaster-JohnsonCareyPublicity (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Johnson in ''Wagon Master'' (1950)]]\nHis first credited role was in Ford's ''[[3 Godfathers]]''; the film is notable for the riding skills demonstrated by both Johnson and star [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]]. He later said the film was the most physically challenging of his career. Ford then suggested a starring role  for him in the 1949 film ''[[Mighty Joe Young (1949 film)|Mighty Joe Young]]''; he played \"Gregg\" opposite [[Terry Moore (actress)|Terry Moore]]. Ford cast him in two of the three films that have come to be known as Ford's cavalry trilogy, all starring [[John Wayne]]: ''[[She Wore a Yellow Ribbon]]'' (1949), and ''[[Rio Grande (film)|Rio Grande]]'' (1950); both roles showcased Johnson's riding ability. Ford also cast Johnson as the lead in ''[[Wagon Master]]'' (1950), one of Ford's favorites.\n\nIn real life, Johnson did not show any bad temper; his demeanor in tense situations was calm but firm. However, although known for avoiding dramas, he had definite boundaries; during the making of ''[[Rio Grande (film)|Rio Grande]]'' he defied Ford, who was notorious for browbeating his actors, and reportedly told him to go to hell. Johnson thought the incident had been forgotten, but Ford did not use him in a film for over a decade. Johnson also appeared in four films of [[Sam Peckinpah]] and had a good relationship with the wayward director. Peckinpah appreciated Johnson's authenticity and lack of acting airs.<ref name=\"Jensen\"/>\n\nJohnson played in supporting roles in [[Shane (film)|''Shane'']] (1953), where he appeared as Chris Calloway, a \"bad guy who makes good\" after being beaten senseless by [[Alan Ladd]], and ''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961) starring [[Marlon Brando]]. In 1964, he worked with Ford again in ''[[Cheyenne Autumn]]''. He also appeared in four Peckinpah-directed films: ''[[Major Dundee]]'' (1965, with [[Charlton Heston]]), ''[[The Wild Bunch]]'' (1969, with [[William Holden]] and [[Robert Ryan]]), and two back-to-back [[Steve McQueen (actor)|Steve McQueen]] films, [[The Getaway (1972 film)|''The Getaway'']] and the rodeo film ''[[Junior Bonner]]'' (both 1972). In 1973, he co-starred as [[Melvin Purvis]] in [[John Milius]]' [[Dillinger (1973 film)|''Dillinger'']] with [[Warren Oates]]; he also appeared in Milius' 1984 film ''[[Red Dawn]]''. In 1975, he played the character Mister in [[Bite the Bullet (film)|''Bite the Bullet'']], starring [[Gene Hackman]] and [[James Coburn]]. He also appeared with [[Charles Bronson]] in 1975's [[Breakheart Pass (1975 film)|''Breakheart Pass'']]. In 1980, he was cast as Sheriff Isum Gorch in ''Soggy Bottom U.S.A.''\n\nJohnson played Bartlett in the 1962-63 season of ''[[Have Gun Will Travel]]'', which featured a short scene of his riding skills. In 1963 Johnson appeared as Spinner on the TV western ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'' in the episode titled Duel at Shiloh.\" {{citation needed|date=September 2019}} In the 1966-67 television season, Johnson appeared as the character Sleeve in all 26 episodes of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] family Western [[The Monroes (1966 TV series)|''The Monroes'']] with co-stars [[Michael Anderson, Jr.]] and [[Barbara Hershey]].<ref name=IMDb-TVography>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0424565/filmoseries Filmography], imdb.com; accessed June 24, 2015.</ref>\n\nHe teamed up with John Wayne again, and director [[Andrew V. McLaglen]], in two films, appearing with [[Rock Hudson]] in [[The Undefeated (1969 film)|''The Undefeated'']] (1969) and in a fairly prominent role in ''[[Chisum]]'' (1970). The apex of Johnson's career was reached in 1971, with Johnson winning an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for his performance as Sam the Lion in ''[[The Last Picture Show]]'', directed by [[Peter Bogdanovich]].\n\nOn the set of ''[[The Train Robbers]]'', in June 1972, he told Nancy Anderson of [[Copley Press|Copley News Service]] that winning the Oscar for ''The Last Picture Show'' was not going to change him and he would not raise his salary request to studios because of it. He continued, \"I grew up on a ranch and I know livestock, so I like working in Westerns. All my life I've been afraid of failure. To avoid it, I've stuck with doing things I know how to do, and it's made me a good living\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Anderson, Nancy|date=June 4, 1972|title=John Wayne A Father Figure On Movie Set in Durango, Mexico|publisher=[[Copley Press|Copley New Service]]|newspaper=[[The Joplin Globe]]}}</ref>\n\nHe played Cap Roundtree in the 1979 miniseries ''[[Sackett#The Sacketts (TV movie)|The Sacketts]]''. He played Sam Bellows in the 1980 film ''[[Ruckus (film)|Ruckus]]''. He co-starred in the 1994 version of ''[[Angels in the Outfield (1994 film)|Angels in the Outfield]]''.\n\nHe continued ranching during the entire time, operating a horse-breeding ranch in [[Sylmar, California]].<ref name=EricksonH-AM/> In addition, he sponsored the Ben Johnson Pro Celebrity Team Roping and Penning competition, held in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]], the proceeds of which are donated to both the Children's Medical Research Inc. and the Children's Hospital of Oklahoma.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nJohnson continued to work almost steadily until his death from a [[heart attack]] at the age of 77.\nOn April 8, 1996, the veteran actor collapsed while visiting his then 96-year-old mother Ollie at Leisure World in [[Mesa, Arizona]], the suburban Phoenix retirement community where they both lived.<ref>{{Citation|title=Actor Ben Johnson dies at 77|newspaper=The Press of Atlantic City|location=Atlantic City, NJ|date=April 9, 1996|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAEAC23EBC095A0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|accessdate=August 31, 2012}}</ref>  Johnson's body was later transported from Arizona to [[Pawhuska, Oklahoma]], for burial at the Pawhuska City Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Actor Buried Near Pawhuska|date=April 15, 1996|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/actor-buried-near-pawhuska/article_558bfc00-f75b-5eba-857c-c6235c9663fb.html|website=Tulsa World|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor his contribution to the motion picture industry, Johnson has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7083 Hollywood Boulevard. In 1982, he was inducted into the [[Western Performers Hall of Fame]] at the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma City. In 1996, [[Tom Thurman]] made a documentary film about Johnson's life, titled ''Ben Johnson: Third Cowboy on the Right'', written by Thurman and Tom Marksbury.<ref name=ThurmanT-TCotR />\n\nThe Ben Johnson Cowboy Museum was opened in honor of Ben Johnson in his hometown of Pawhuska, OK in June 2019. The museum showcases the life and career of Ben Johnson, as well as his father, Ben Johnson, Sr., who was also a world champion cowboy. In addition to the Ben Johnsons, the museum also features other world champion cowboys and cowgirls, famous ranches (like the one Ben grew up on), and cowboy artists and craftsmen, all from the area where Ben grew up.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Ben Johnson Cowboy Museum |url=http://www.facebook.com/benjohnsoncowboymuseum |website=Facebook |accessdate=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Ben Johnson Memorial Steer Roping and the International Roundup Cavalcade, the world's largest amateur rodeo, are held annually in Pawhuska, Oklahoma.<ref name=\"EOHC-Pawhuska\">{{cite web|title=Johnson, Ben, Jr. {{!}} The Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture|author=May, Jon D.|url=http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=JO004|website=www.okhistory.org|accessdate=April 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA one-and-a-quarter-size bronze sculpture by John D. Free of Ben Johnson riding a horse and roping a steer was commissioned and  produced in Pawhuska, Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://assets.mediaspanonline.com/prod/12956314/pcn-2016-05-11-c-005.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012021751/http://assets.mediaspanonline.com/prod/12956314/pcn-2016-05-11-c-005.pdf |archivedate=2016-10-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film (actor and stuntman)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1939\n| ''[[The Fighting Gringo (1939 film)|The Fighting Gringo]]''\n| Mexican Barfly\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''[[The Outlaw]]''\n| Deputy\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''Bordertown Gun Fighters\n| Messenger\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1944\n| ''The Pinto Bandit\n| Race Contestant\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1944\n| ''[[Tall in the Saddle]]''\n| Townsman / Stuntman\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1944\n| ''[[Nevada (1944 film)|Nevada]]''\n| Saloon Patron / Stunt Double: [[Robert Mitchum]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1945\n| ''Corpus Christi Bandits''\n| 2nd Stage Driver\n| Uncredited \n|-\n| 1945\n| ''[[The Naughty Nineties]]''\n| Coach Driver\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1946\n| ''[[Badman's Territory]]''\n| Deputy Marshal\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1947\n| ''[[Wyoming (1947 film)|Wyoming]]''\n| Cowhand\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1947\n| ''[[Angel and the Badman]]''\n| Stuntman\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''The Gallant Legion''\n| Texas Ranger\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Fort Apache (film)|Fort Apache]]''\n| Stunt Double: [[Henry Fonda]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[3 Godfathers]]''\n| Posse Man #1 / Stuntman\n| Johnson was also a stuntman but wasn't credited for it.\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Red River (1948 film)|Red River]]''\n| Stuntman\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1949\n| ''[[She Wore a Yellow Ribbon]]''\n| Sgt. Tyree\n|\n|-\n| 1949\n| ''[[Mighty Joe Young (1949 film)|Mighty Joe Young]]''\n| Gregg\n| \n|-\n| 1950\n| ''[[Wagon Master]]''\n| Travis Blue\n|\n|-\n| 1950\n| ''[[Rio Grande (film)|Rio Grande]]''\n| Trooper Travis Tyree\n| \n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[Fort Defiance (film)|Fort Defiance]]''\n| Ben Shelby\n|\n|-\n| 1952\n| ''[[Wild Stallion]]''\n| Dan Light \n|\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''\n| Chris Calloway\n| \n|-\n| 1955\n| ''[[Oklahoma! (1955 film)|Oklahoma!]]\n| Wrangler / Stuntman\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Rebel in Town]]''\n| Frank Mason\n| \n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[War Drums]]''\n| Luke Fargo\n| \n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Slim Carter]]''\n| Montana Burriss\n|\n|-\n| 1958\n| ''[[Fort Bowie (film)|Fort Bowie]]''\n| Capt. Thomas Thompson\n| \n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[Ten Who Dared]]''\n| George Bradley\n| \n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]''\n| Bob Amory\n| \n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Tomboy and the Champ]]''\n| Uncle Jim\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Cheyenne Autumn]]'' \n| Trooper Plumtree\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Major Dundee]]''\n| Sergeant Chillum\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[The Rare Breed]]''\n| Jeff Harter\n| \n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Will Penny]]''\n| Alex \n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Hang 'Em High]]''\n| Marshal Dave Bliss \n| \n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[The Wild Bunch]]''\n| Tector Gorch\n| \n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[The Undefeated (1969 film)|The Undefeated]]''\n| Short Grub\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Chisum]]''\n| James Pepper\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[The Last Picture Show]]''\n| Sam the Lion\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br />[[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]<br />[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br /